<Author>Marco_PoloHongKong
<Content>"Normally downgrade clients" at The Padma Bali We stayed at the Padma Bali for 6 nights, it was meant to be the 'luxury beginning' of our 4 week backpacking tour of Indonesia. We decided that we'd go 5 star at the beginning to get our energies up before roughing it for the next 4 weeks.We'd booked a Deluxe Chalet Room (US$150/night on the internet). Unfortunately, whilst checking in I saw the word DOWNGRADE next to my name on the computer. The receptionist carried on checking us in without mentioning the downgrade. Before she gave me the keycard I asked her whether we were getting the Deluxe Chalet Room, as booked. The receptionist confirmed that we were getting a Deluxe Chalet Room, tomorrow night. Tonight we would have to stay in a standard room, because the Chalet Rooms were full. I asked how that could be, as I had made my booking 7 months earlier, and had fully paid for it at the time of booking.The receptionist could offer no explanation, so I asked to see the manager. He was also unable to offer an explanation. I explained that most 4 / 5 star hotels upgraded rather than downgraded when the booked room category was full. He explained that The Padma Bali did not follow this policy, he then said it is normal for us to downgrade ! . I then explained that he'd taken money from me, and then failed to provide me with the goods for which I'd paid, this is known as theft in most countries. He then offered me a massage at the spa in compensation !Anyway, the hotel wouldn't budge, they were downgrading me and would not compensate me financially. Beyond this significant flaw in their customer service I would surmise that the Padma Bali is a fairly anemic resort hotel. It is very clean, well kept and has good facilities. However, it lacked any sense of character, you could have been in a hotel anywhere. Cliched cultural packaging, piped music and far too many people characterises our experience here. It was a sort of simulacrum of being in Indonesia rather than actually being in Indonesia.The surrounding area (Legian/Kuta) is a horrendous pile of tourist tat, overpriced tacky shops and low quality western food restaurants. It's neither a tropical oasis, nor anywhere near an experience of Balinese culture.This was the most expensive, and by far the worst, of the 11 hotels we stayed at during our 4 week tour of Indonesia. Needless to say that I deeply regret staying there and would never return. 
