<Author>denny_perth
<Content>Nice Hotel but had a few problems My wife, 11 year old son and I stayed for 9 nights at the Padma in March 2008. All in all it is a very nice hotel with beautiful grounds and very friendly and willing staff. Just a few incidents tainted our stay.We stayed in a family room. The room was clean but with the powerfull smell of anti mosquito tablets that they change every night. However, I would rather have the smell than be bitten alive by mossies. However, we still tended to find a couple every night mainly in the bathroom. Also, the family rooms are miles away from the pool. We had room 144 which is adjacent to the tennis courts and fitness centre. It was a 5 minute walk to the pool.I took my laptop and purchased internet in the room. for the first four days I could not connect in the morning until thier IT people either came to the room (in the afternoon) or sorted some system error. Quite frustrating when you need to check your email and have paid for the in room service. After the first four days it was fine.Remote for the DVD player didnt work when we arived but a phone call to reception had someone there within 20 minutes and it was fixed.Room service arrived within about half an hour of ordering but very often the food was barely warm when we received it.Nice pool but not enough loungers necessitating people booking them with towels before breakfast. I would not stoop to this practise but probably to our detrament.Breakfast was plentifull. My wife found a bug in her rice porridge one morning which I pointed out to the waitress. The waitress looked at it, laughed and took it away and that was the end of it! I think she just was not trained on how to deal with this situation and it was more of an embarrassed reaction. Unfortunately my wife did not trust the hotel food after that. One of the two toasters broke one morning and I was surprised they didnt have a spare which lead to long queue at the remaining toaster for that morning! Frustrating because after a couple of days of over eating I resorted to toast only for my breakfast. Also the toaster had a timer on it that many people didnt realise and would be waiting a long time for their toast when the thing wasnt even switched on! Coffee was often luke warm, I politely mentioned it one morning and the reaction was amazing. They made me fresh coffee and had three people running (yes, literally running) around to rectify the situation. A total contrast to the bug waitress incident!Another thing that bothered me a little, but many people would see it as a positive thing, was that there always seemed to be someone knocking on the door! I feel that the cleaning crew could perform all of the little individual things that people kept knocking on the door for, ie, change the mosquito tablet, check the minibar, have you got enough towels, check the toilet!! Yes, We had this little guy kept knocking on the door asking if everything is ok and insisted on cming in, looking around and checking the toilet flushed. It seemed so bizarre I phoned reception to check he was authentic and not just some guy casing the room!As with any Hotel, in house goods  services are three (or more) times of what you will pay on the street. Unfortunately, the street hawkers were so bad constantly and persistently pestering you that we were getting to the stage where we didnt want to leave the hotel. We found on our last day that if you venture north of Padma Street into Seminyak, it all stops and you can stroll down the street shopping un hindered! It was as if we were in a different place!We tried to spend some time on the public beach at Kuta so that I could buggy board with my son. We immediately had six women (with the big hats) wanting to massage, sell, platt, etc. They were so persistant I started to get annoyed and my wife told me to go in the sea and leave her to it. When in the sea I looked back and saw that she was alone reading her book. When I returned and enquired how she got rid of them, she told me she gave them money to leave her in peace! Probably not a good idea but it seemed to work.If we ever return to beautiful Bali, we will be staying at Sanur or Ubud where they have some lovely hotels and the hawking is at a minumum. 
